The defendant Jaquay A Hudnall was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Drive or Operate Vehicle w/o Consent [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.23(3).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
In the Wisconsin State Prison System. Credit
for 4 days time served if revoked. Court advised defendant on Extended Confinement or "bad time".
Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

25% of prison funds, collected by Department of Corrections, to go toward all court ordered monetary obligations, with restitution having first priority, all other monetary obligations thereafter, if revoked.

miscConds.notes: AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
Maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs; random urine screens; if deemed appropriate.  No contact with victim, Judith U.
Pay restitution in the amount of $85.00 to Judith U.  Failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment being entered.

Provide a DNA sample; pay MANDATORY DNA surcharge; failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment being entered.  Pay all court costs, fees, and surcharges; and pay all applicable fees of supervision. Failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment being entered.  A payment plan for all monetary obligations is to be established by Department of Corrections, Probation and Parole. All unpaid monetary balances at the end of said period will convert to a civil judgment.
Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms.
Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored.
